				\begin{document}$$D \, = \, \frac{0.9\lambda }{\beta \cos \theta }$$\end{document} where λ, θ and β are the X-ray wavelength (1.5406 Å), Bragg diffraction angle and full-width at half-maximum (FWHM), respectively. The grain size of the CuO phase in the CuO–ZnO nanocomposite films decreased with the increase in the atom % of Zn (Table 1). For CdTe-ZnO nanocomposite films, Potter et al. [29] observed a decrease in grain size with increasing CdTe content. The decrease in grain size was attributed by these authors to the interruption of host material with the increase in the atom % of dopant. In a recent report, Manu and Khadar [25] observed a decrease in the size of Fe-doped nanocrystals of TiO2 with the increase in the doping % of Fe. Because of self-purification mechanism, nanoparticles always have a tendency to expel the dopant atoms due to which the concentration of dopant near the grain boundaries will be larger than that near the core of the doped nanoparticles. The increase in the number of dopant atoms near the growing surface of nanoparticles would result in a decrease in the growth sites provided by host atoms leading to a decrease in the size of the doped nanoparticles with the increase in the dopant concentration.

Figure 7 shows the Arrhenius plots of conductivity of the CuO–ZnO nanocomposite films containing different Zn at % over the temperature range from 315 to 429 K. The dependence of conductivity on temperature can be represented by the Arrhenius equation:1σ(T)=σ0exp(-EA/kT)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
