				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sigma (T) = \sigma_{0} \exp ( - E_{\text{A}} /kT)$$\end{document}where σ0 is the pre-exponential factor, k is the Boltzmann constant and T is the temperature. The activation energies (EA) of the films for charge transport were estimated from the slope of the Arrhenius plots. The activation energy for conduction determined from the plots is 0.2044, 0.1844 and 0.1626 eV, respectively, for the samples containing Zn at% of ~ 3, ~ 8 and ~ 40. Figure 3a–d shows that the size of the particles seen in the AFM images decreased with the increase in the Zn at% in the samples, thereby increasing the packing density of the particles creating stronger interparticle contacts that can be inferred to be non-resistive from the decrease in the activation energy for DC conduction. Bian et al. [9] reported that in ZnO–CuO nanocomposite samples, band bending helped easy transfer of electrons and holes from ZnO to CuO phase. The lower activation energy for conduction of samples containing higher atom % of Zn in the present study indicates this type of easy transfer of charges from ZnO to CuO phase due to band bending (Fig. 8). Hall measurements showed that the mobility of charge carriers, which were confirmed to be electrons from the negative sign of the Hall coefficients, increased from 1.5 to 7.5 cm2 V−1 s−1 with the increase in Zn at% from ~ 3 to ~ 40 in the film samples. The decrease in the activation energy for DC conduction and the increase in the charge mobility with the increase in the Zn at% in the samples point to the non-resistive nature of the interparticle contacts in the film samples.Fig. 7
